<br>
From the book of cheating, chapter 3 verse 16<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> quoting Krilen from other threads is cheating<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The point that went over your head is this: you whip out the &quot;old school mage&quot; thing when I'm not even talking about mages. Cong c&amp;p.<br>
<br>
to balanz now,<br>
<br>
Second of all, picking on grammar or poor word choice is lame. Semantics on a message board just provide a healthy speed bump... if I said I didn't consider myself attacking ylaine, don't go and bring up a word, look it up in the dictionary, and spin it so that it contradicts whatever else I just said. Take out the word malicious if you like, replace it with chocolate. You can't go wrong with chocolate, unless you're allergic. I don't see why a post can't be malicious and the poster of it not, unless you conform 100% to the words in a certain part of a book and completely ignore other parts of the book. But hey, I don't use that book, mine doesn't say anything about motive, just says it's &quot;evil, blah blah blah&quot;, and evil is subjective.<br>
<br>
Now, see how refreshingly useless semantics is? &gt;&lt;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 From www.dictionary.com: ad hom·i·nem adj. <br>
Appealing to personal considerations rather than to logic or reason: Debaters should avoid ad hominem arguments that question their opponents' motives.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
What part of that don't you understand?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't give a crap about her motives. What I see is a post that conveys her opinion under the smokescreen of a historical document. I make a post to help dispel this smoke screen.<br>
<br>
PS. so is pointing out an ad hominem argument like, the ultimate hipocrisy? I think so.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 'nuff said.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
please elaborate<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Put up or shut up. Disagree or agree, point out new facts, propose alternative interpretations of event, show flaws in reasoning, but don't argue that Ylaine is purposely trying to hurt mages by lying to them.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Please read the 2 quotes from me you quoted before this quote. I'm not even bothering to argue against ylaine's points. All I wanted to do in this thread is make sure everyone understands that it's a persuasive argument and not a historical document.<br>
<br>
Want me to prove it? You can't really 'prove' something like that, compared to say, proving a mathematical equation or something. Maybe you could if you whipped out dictionary.com. I also don't wanna pick out 1-2 quotes and just point out that in some weird icelandic religion they're contradictory or something.<br>
<br>
Observe the spin she puts on this quote. Spin does not have any place in historical document.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> While not as powerful as Wizards they should be atleast a better option than summoning Mod Rods for *clerics* to nuke with<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
She attributes the fact that it's better for us to rod clerics to nuke as a problem with our offensive capability. When in fact...<br>
<br>
It has nothing to do with offensive capability. Our nukes are still better than cleric nukes. Our nukes would have to be insanely good or clerics insanely bad to make it more efficient for us to nuke than rod.<br>
<br>
It's not a problem with nukes, it's the fact that mod rods give back more mana than they take to cost, something I'm extremely happy about. She, however, makes it seem to the reader that it's a problem with our nukes &gt;&lt; a very chocolate thing to do in a historical document.<br>
<br>
What would be better, a mage making rods for a cleric to nuke with, or a mage making rods for a 2nd mage to nuke with?<br>
<br>
If these are the only 2 options, it's still better for the mage to nuke.<br>
<br>
Keep in mind I have no brain, so I can't compute these things. Perhaps a fix would be to give mages a no-drop ultimate rod. Not sure if that could possibly fix it though, since, no brain. Or rather, I'm too lazy to think about them for more than 3.4 seconds. This thread is not about the power of rods anyway.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I'm just trying to educate others on the history of Magicians,<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here is where it makes her opinion look like history.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> and hopefully help them see that we're not some mod rod class and we don't deserve to be forgotten as damage dealers <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And here is where she draws unneccessary conclusions from unrelated evidence, which I'm sure is some more of your ad-hominem-esque fallacy crap.<br>
<br>
The fact that we have had damage spells in the past has nothing to do with the present in this game. I could as easily argue that &quot;We ARE some mod rod class, and we DO deserve to be forgotten&quot; and it wouldn't be any more relevent to a historical document than the above quote from ylaine's post.<br>
